        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat(examples): safeTok ↔ OpenClaw DM bridge",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n1. Use OpenClaw with Claude OAuth — no Anthropic API key needed.\n2. Communicate with your OpenClaw agent via Nostr — specifically safeTok NIP-44 DMs.\n\n## Evidence\n\nRunning live — the screenshot above shows a full DM conversation flowing through the bridge. The bridge was deployed on a production OpenClaw instance; incoming safeTok DMs are decrypted, routed to the assistant session, and the assistant reply is encrypted and published back to the Nostr relay. Seen-event deduplication (persisted to disk) prevents duplicate replies across restarts.\n\n## What this adds\n\nA self-contained example bridge that connects [safeTok](https://safetok.me) to OpenClaw via the Gateway WebSocket API — end-to-end encrypted, decentralized, no middleman.\n\n![safeTok DMs appearing in OpenClaw Control UI](https://github.com/ductapecode/openclaw/raw/feat/safetok-bridge-example/examples/safetok-bridge/docs/preview.png)\n\n## How it works\n\n```\nsafeTok user\n    │  NIP-44 DM (kind:4) on Nostr relays\n    ▼\nbridge.mjs\n    │  gateway WebSocket (chat.send / chat.history)\n    ▼\nOpenClaw session  →  assistant reply\n    │  NIP-44 encrypted response\n    ▼\nsafeTok user\n```\n\n## Files\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `bridge.mjs` | Main bridge — env-var configured, no hardcoded secrets |\n| `nip44.mjs` | safeTok NIP-44 crypto primitives |\n| `README.md` | Setup guide with demo screenshot |",
